[{"sha":"751fa61d5a49fc4c232b3f48461f55a15c59064f","author":{"name":"Frank Harrison","email":"86a8c2da8527a1c6978bdca6d7986fe14ae147fe@doublethefish.com"},"message":"overlapping act| Adds output showing the overlapping act() call stacks

The intent here is to help developers, like myself, save hours of effort
trying to diagnose overlapping act() calls when they get `"You seem to
have overlapping act() calls"`

This is 'good enough' for my purposes, but probably needs someone a bit
more familiar with the react ecosystem to make it production-ready.
Specifically the `uuid4()`, `stringifyActiveActStacks()` and
`captureScope()` functions need some scrutiny.

I am putting this up early to help others who have hit the same problem.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/doublethefish/react/commits/751fa61d5a49fc4c232b3f48461f55a15c59064f"}]

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce","author":{"name":"Maozhou, Ge","email":"6af58e7e67bf1b9026edca922343d4896082d124@intel.com"},"message":"fix code style","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce"},{"sha":"c2e2b4f7ae7e4dd25d2d310d237282ced213839e","author":{"name":"A. Change-Id: If40bdf07d6d58d0dd354e8ec1405e79340aa1d2d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/9549bb1df8516a1bbcf87a19c0bf8f634dc9d615"},{"sha":"8aee7ba4d7279d61a54adad6af72b049092fa5d0","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Enable SPMD passes.

- Add SPMD related passes in the GPU compilation pipeline. This includes the domain
  isolator at the start of HLO optimizations, and domain remover, sharding propagation,
  and SPMD partitioner after a set of HLO optimizations.
- Change GpuLayoutAssignment to initialize channel constraints with a default
  constructed constraint (since collective communication ops with channel_id, i.e, cross
  host/module collective ops, do not require any specific layout constraint).

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Attempt to fix broken adjoint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc"},{"sha":"0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Implement gradient for SparseTensorDenseMatMul with complex args","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d"},{"sha":"8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce","author":{"name":"Maozhou, Ge","email":"6af58e7e67bf1b9026edca922343d4896082d124@intel.com"},"message":"fix code style","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce"},{"sha":"9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"2227b17c3edc64ffc05afb8e2c3d063a6ccec65a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Define dependent dialects for tf-functional-to-executor-conversion pass

the first quantize ops in the pairs.

When the new Suspense cache was integrated (so that startTransition could be used) I removed a couple of optimizations between the backend and frontend that reduced bridge traffic when e.g. dehydrated paths were inspected for elements that had not rendered since previously inspected. This commit re-adds those optimizations as well as an additional test with a bug fix that I noticed while reading the backend code.

There are two remaining TODO items as of this commit:

- Don't over-eagerly refresh the cache in our ping-for-updates handler

I will addres both in subsequent commits.

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. Use the pre-built scheduler (which includes a check for 'window' being defined in order to load the right scheduler implementation) rather than just directly importing a version of the scheduler that relies on window. Since the scheduling profiler's code runs partially in a web worker, it can't rely on window.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ChrisDobby/react/commits/4190a34588ec0b05aac6f050ec656ec4b3f005d7"},{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ChrisDobby/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

Currently ROCm TF cotnainers use the `install_pip_packages.sh` script to install the Python pip package-manager.
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/Dockerfile.rocm#L102
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/install/install_pip_packages.sh#L20-L23

Starting 01/23/2021, we started getting the following error while building TF containers for ROCM CI (when calling `get-pip.py` for Python2)

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "get-pip.py", line 24226, in <module>
    main()
  File "get-pip.py", line 199, in main
    bootstrap(tmpdir=tmpdir)
  File "get-pip.py", line 82, in bootstrap
    from pip._internal.cli.main import main as pip_entry_point
  File "/tmp/tmpWkL0gn/pip.zip/pip/_internal/cli/main.py", line 60
    sys.stderr.write(f"ERROR: {exc}")
```

The cause seems to be an update to the `get-pip.py` script, which now picks the version `pip-21.0` (previously it was `pip-20.3.4`).
`pip-21.0` drops support for Python2.7 (as indicated by the following warning message)
```
DEPRECATION: Python 2.7 reached the end of its life on January 1st, 2020.
Please upgrade your Python as Python 2.7 is no longer maintained.
pip 21.0 will drop support for Python 2.7 in January 2021.
More details about Python 2 support in pip can be found at
https://pip.pypa.io/en/latest/development/release-process/#python-2-support
pip 21.0 will remove support for this functionality.
```

It seems that there is now a Python 2.7 specific version of the `get-pip.py` script that we need to use, and that is what this commit does","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pedro-r-marques/tensorflow/commits/5a3ac7eea0cb61af8e0d25419b174ead0a6a73ac"},{"sha":"dde133c3f3edc717b0fa2b08f798e0d6c473d8bc","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fixing a bug that concat can create extra constraints to buffer sharing.

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think

trying to diagnose overlapping act() calls when they get `"You seem to
have overlapping act() calls"`

more familiar with the react ecosystem to make it production-ready.

Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"remove unused `if_libtpu`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8"},{"sha":"d439d8c6d4137e0bc468a2de06e41b375029ee92","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR] Add dependency from "lhlo_ops_structs_inc_gen" to "lhlo" target.

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"remove unused `if_libtpu`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8"},{"sha":"af4f378fbc3a74bd871b7b1bc4199816e7d27ee8","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46731 from vnvo2409:gradients

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

Signed-off-by: Prashant Kumar <prashantk@polymagelabs.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/cbb993eca65f0eeb1d63f0699190edbae43a9dd1"},{"sha":"04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Prefer generator expressions over list comprehensions

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"7133856f198068e991e1f3c9b2c0dea3d92cb8d0","author":{"name":"Jiri Simsa","email":"b53bfee97ac78a1d2afd0ef6138945f352c1fa9d@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data] Avoid concurrent cancellation of child CancellationManager which causes a deadlock.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 359432458
Change-Id: I08e98c3d3a211e8522e42d9ae600b44819b797db","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/6130226a8c1b8787adf4c49bdb0fff5292bd861c"},{"sha":"53ff2339b3c05a6efbe5bdbdd6c40b8973fb8e17","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"TensorBoard callback: handle exceptions due to concurrent profiling

Failure to profile should not be fatal.

In addition to handling exceptions, try to prevent callbacks from interfering with other clients (including other callbacks) by ensuring a callback only calls profiler.stop() if it successfully called profiler.start().

Part of alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544.
Prevents unhandled exceptions from crashing the program when setting environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING=1.

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

- Do not call GetNcclAllReduceConfig() when checking if the all-reduce is degenerate,
  as that can fail if the reduction computation does not match. Use
  GetNcclCollectiveConfigForMlir instead.
- This allows otherwise degenerate all-reduce with an arbitrary reduction computation
  to be compiled without failures (and mapped to just a copy).

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:

Signed-off-by: Prashant Kumar <prashantk@polymagelabs.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/cbb993eca65f0eeb1d63f0699190edbae43a9dd1"},{"sha":"04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Prefer generator expressions over list comprehensions

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"6130226a8c1b8787adf4c49bdb0fff5292bd861c","author":{"name":"Jaesung Chung","email":"935e11c5b050a3a02c4f0e08de55daf431709deb@google.com"},"message":"Make sure that the dilated conversion patterns are safe to replace.

The generated SpaceToBatchND op by the ConvLSTM2D keras layer, is being used in
the multiple places, which means it is not eligible for applying the dilated
conversion patterns. This change adds use count checks to avoid creating
malformed MLIR.

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to

Failure to profile should not be fatal.

In addition to handling exceptions, try to prevent callbacks from interfering with other clients (including other callbacks) by ensuring a callback only calls profiler.stop() if it successfully called profiler.start().

Part of alternative to https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46544.
Prevents unhandled exceptions from crashing the program when setting environment variable TF_DISABLE_PROFILING=1.

`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an

This is usually happen when post-training quantizing the model which has custom
ops on the output. The existing modifying io lib will produce the back to back
quantize op pairs which will cause accuracy dropping.

This cl tries to identify the back to back quantize op pairs pattern and remove
the first quantize ops in the pairs.

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/itsag/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"},{"sha":"40d61903ad5b2952e531a3c3d9dfd474fe066fd1","author":{"name":"Ajay","email":"1202fcdef5f9fe6115e1ee4c45e58be06c9c9d82@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #1 from facebook/master

- Add SPMD related passes in the GPU compilation pipeline. This includes the domain
  isolator at the start of HLO optimizations, and domain remover, sharding propagation,
  and SPMD partitioner after a set of HLO optimizations.
- Change GpuLayoutAssignment to initialize channel constraints with a default
  constructed constraint (since collective communication ops with channel_id, i.e, cross
  host/module collective ops, do not require any specific layout constraint).

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Attempt to fix broken adjoint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc"},{"sha":"0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Implement gradient for SparseTensorDenseMatMul with complex args","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d"},{"sha":"8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce","author":{"name":"Maozhou, Ge","email":"6af58e7e67bf1b9026edca922343d4896082d124@intel.com"},"message":"fix code style","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/8e5924dc70b36358a941221b768c100efc7529ce"},{"sha":"9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that

the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that

[{"sha":"9ddf72c22808e14c054dda5507b376dfacf07fa1","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"remove unused `if_libtpu`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8"},{"sha":"332c19f246b07c6351fc714232de354546205d8b","author":{"name":"Hanhan Wang","email":"17db91a825a40156b2c20ef2022824cbafd12aac@google.com"},"message":"Add support for lowering mhlo.pad to linalg.pad_tensor

the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via

`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Attempt to fix broken adjoint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc"},{"sha":"0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Implement gradient for SparseTensorDenseMatMul with complex args","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d"},{"sha":"9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below

Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:
* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rickhanlonii/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"}]

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"The colocation constraint added in the embedding_lookup sometimes conflicts with externally specified tf.device() placement scope, causing runtime errors in the placer like this:

```
Check failed: TF_GetCode(status_) == TF_OK (3 vs. 0) Cannot colocate nodes {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}} and {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1}}: Cannot merge devices with incompatible tasks: '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:1/device:CPU:0' and '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0'
	 [[{{node while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}}]] while calling function "train"
```

To avoid this issue, this change resets the tf.device context before applying the colocation constraint around the gather op in the embedding_lookup function.

Changes:

```
* backend/s3: Support for AWS Single-Sign On (SSO) cached credentials
```

Updated via:

```
go get github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go@v1.37.0
go mod tidy
```

Please note that Terraform CLI will not initiate or perform the AWS SSO login flow. It is expected that you have already performed the SSO login flow using AWS CLI using the `aws sso login` command, or by some other mechanism before executing Terraform. More precisely, this credential handling must find a valid non-expired access token for the AWS SSO user portal URL in `~/.aws/sso/cache`. If a cached token is not found, is expired, or the file is malformed an error will be returned.

You can use configure AWS SSO credentials from the AWS shared configuration file by specifying the required keys in the profile:

```
sso_account_id
sso_region
sso_role_name
sso_start_url
```

For example, the following defines a profile "devsso" and specifies the AWS SSO parameters that defines the target account, role, sign-on portal, and the region where the user portal is located. Note: all SSO arguments must be provided, or an error will be returned.

```
[profile devsso]
sso_start_url = https:my-sso-portal.awsapps.com/start
sso_role_name = SSOReadOnlyRole
sso_region = us-east-1
sso_account_id = 123456789012
```

Additional Resources

* [Configuring the AWS CLI to use AWS Single Sign-On](https:docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/cli-configure-sso.html)

replaced with the global -chdir flag, which is specified before any

most commands. The only command which still supports a path argument is
fmt, which also supports "-" to indicate receiving configuration from
standard input.

Any invocation of a command with an invalid trailing path parameter will
result in a short error message, pointing at the -chdir alternative.

There are many test updates in this commit, almost all of which are
migrations from using positional arguments to specify a working
directory. Because of the layer at which these tests run, we are unable
to use the -chdir argument, so the churn in test files is larger than

the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

[{"sha":"9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add StrictMode level prop and createRoot unstable_strictModeLevel option (#20849)

* The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

A subsequent commit will add additional DEV warnings:

is not of pulp group and removes that requirement.
Ti achieve this it  does the following:
1) Ignores checking the 'pulp' permissions in the import path. This job
   is best left to pulp (https://pulp.plan.io/issues/7549)

   rather than scanning the directory. This removes the requirement of
   foreman/vagrant user having to check a pulp directory.

   pauses on error and requires the user to skip and delete the content
   view version.

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think

channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"remove unused `if_libtpu`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8"},{"sha":"b8c9a576c90a0aba678760b4c0d85ea0a044b007","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA/GPU] Re-enable h-loop-fusion to share operands with users.

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"The colocation constraint added in the embedding_lookup sometimes conflicts with externally specified tf.device() placement scope, causing runtime errors in the placer like this:

```
Check failed: TF_GetCode(status_) == TF_OK (3 vs. 0) Cannot colocate nodes {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}} and {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1}}: Cannot merge devices with incompatible tasks: '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:1/device:CPU:0' and '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0'
	 [[{{node while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}}]] while calling function "train"
```

To avoid this issue, this change resets the tf.device context before applying the colocation constraint around the gather op in the embedding_lookup function.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"The colocation constraint added in the embedding_lookup sometimes conflicts with externally specified tf.device() placement scope, causing runtime errors in the placer like this:

```
Check failed: TF_GetCode(status_) == TF_OK (3 vs. 0) Cannot colocate nodes {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}} and {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1}}: Cannot merge devices with incompatible tasks: '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:1/device:CPU:0' and '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0'
	 [[{{node while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}}]] while calling function "train"
```

To avoid this issue, this change resets the tf.device context before applying the colocation constraint around the gather op in the embedding_lookup function.

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"ddeb3ab137a3b8d8019582ee93ac3ed7f403cc26","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #47355 from charmasaur:complex_sparse_grad

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Re-enable padded MatrixBatchVectorMultiply with sdot with bugfix.

Both channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr are modified in the asm code
of DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate. This CL marks
channel_scales_ptr as modified at the end of the asm block so the compiler
knows the register will change during execution.

More importantly, the value of channel_scales_ptr and row_sums_ptr
are now recomputed at the top of the batch loop, as their values are
only related to row and not to the batch index.

Test coverage of the padded branch was also improved in this CL.
Some of the tests that appears to test padded mode weren't really
running, because the code requires large inputs (128 * 128 or larger)
to use the padded optimization. This CL adds two large input tests.
I have verified that the new per-channel test fails without
this CL and succeeds with it.

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"},{"sha":"751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Attempt to fix broken adjoint","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/751a3971461230fbee5d65976127f9ed4b3009fc"},{"sha":"0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Implement gradient for SparseTensorDenseMatMul with complex args","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/0623c04b1e4385dc8cb85e037763f04b8686945d"},{"sha":"9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04","author":{"name":"Harry Slatyer","email":"6ce37a6d8c18c0879ebe6a41be76538cce17b6f8@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix SparseTensorDenseMatMul test with large matrices

For a start the test wasn't being run. But it also had a problem where
the test in the complex case was trivial (the matrices) were all zeros:
it was creating `x` in `[0,1]`, then turning it into `(x+1j*x)/2` via
`_maybe_complex`, and then setting all the values with magnitude below
`0.8` to `0`. But even `(1+1j)/2` (the value with largest magntidue that
`x` can take) only has a magnitude of about `0.7`. Fix is just to create
complex numbers as `x+x*1j` instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/9aabe5117c9d0d29a90c365a4c393bcf47549e04"},{"sha":"10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6","author":{"name":"Måns Nilsson","email":"f429d3ebc62bd10906847170cf9cafede1026db8@arm.com"},"message":"TFLM: Run FVP job for Github CI only","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/10ecae544b393d56479d612c269bef8f4c6ad9f6"},{"sha":"5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"remove unused `if_libtpu`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/5585c0c733a0b895a6fb5ee1ab33cca4a5a920b8"},{"sha":"343a807ef023b61361a3cdf804a6b3ced363d462","author":{"name":"Nat Jeffries","email":"2e09a75ee8475320aa1ac5230cf082097d8413be@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix buildifier issue","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/343a807ef023b61361a3cdf804a6b3ced363d462"},{"sha":"a8b7311fbd999e257387289cc3034fdcff8384da","author":{"name":"Nat Jeffries","email":"2e09a75ee8475320aa1ac5230cf082097d8413be@gmail.com"},"message":"Use xa_nnlib for conv for Fusion F1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/a8b7311fbd999e257387289cc3034fdcff8384da"},{"sha":"eb9728c18996fb861d7977a4b757879af19be2bb","author":{"name":"Nat Jeffries","email":"2e09a75ee8475320aa1ac5230cf082097d8413be@gmail.com"},"message":"Clean up conv prepare + eval","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/eb9728c18996fb861d7977a4b757879af19be2bb"}]

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"The colocation constraint added in the embedding_lookup sometimes conflicts with externally specified tf.device() placement scope, causing runtime errors in the placer like this:

```
Check failed: TF_GetCode(status_) == TF_OK (3 vs. 0) Cannot colocate nodes {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}} and {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1}}: Cannot merge devices with incompatible tasks: '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:1/device:CPU:0' and '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0'
	 [[{{node while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}}]] while calling function "train"
```

To avoid this issue, this change resets the tf.device context before applying the colocation constraint around the gather op in the embedding_lookup function.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"The colocation constraint added in the embedding_lookup sometimes conflicts with externally specified tf.device() placement scope, causing runtime errors in the placer like this:

```
Check failed: TF_GetCode(status_) == TF_OK (3 vs. 0) Cannot colocate nodes {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}} and {{colocation_node StatefulPartitionedCall/while/body/_66/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1}}: Cannot merge devices with incompatible tasks: '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:1/device:CPU:0' and '/job:tpu_host_worker/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0'
	 [[{{node while/gradients_1/while/embedding_lookup/Gather_1_grad/Size}}]] while calling function "train"
```

To avoid this issue, this change resets the tf.device context before applying the colocation constraint around the gather op in the embedding_lookup function.
